<h1>
Attorney General Ellison issues a statement on the abrupt closure of Argosy Universityâs Twin Cities campus
</h1>
 <!--TITLE-->

 
 
    <p>The Minnesota Attorney General has issued a statement to  inform Minnesota students of potential options they have in light of the abrupt  closure of Argosy University&rsquo;s Twin Cities campus on March 8, 2019.Â  &ldquo;It is deeply troubling that hard-working  students who took out student loans to further their education have had their education  and livelihoods jeopardized by the sudden closure of Argosy by its owners,&rdquo;  Attorney General Ellison said.</p>
    <h2>Argosy University&rsquo;s Closure</h2>
    <p>Argosy was owned by a California non-profit corporation, the Dream Center Foundation  but, in January, Dream Center suddenly announced that it was entering &ldquo;receivership,&rdquo;  in which a third party is appointed to take control of the company to manage  and sell off assets.Â  Subsequently, the U.S.  Department of Education announced on February 27 that it was denying Argosy&rsquo;s  prior application for change of ownership and revoking the school&rsquo;s eligibility  to receive federal financial aid due to its failure to meet financial responsibility  standards.Â  As part of its revocation of  Argosy&rsquo;s eligibility for federal financial aid, the U.S. Department of  Education found that Argosy mishandled federal student aid funds and student  stipends. Argosy confirmed that its Twin Cities campus would close on March 8.</p>
    <p>The Department of  Education has also reported that it is in the process of identifying Argosy students who were disbursed federal  loans for the current term and cancelling those disbursements. Â The Department states that the cancellation of  these disbursements is being done automatically, with adjustments made to  students&rsquo; loan balances to reflect the cancellation. For current Pell Grant  recipients transferring to a school and starting classes before July 1, 2019,  the Department states that the financial aid office of students&rsquo; new schools  will be able to determine the student&rsquo;s remaining 2018-19 Pell Grant  eligibility. </p>
    <h2>Transfer Options for Impacted Students</h2>
    <p>Students who were currently attending Argosy should  carefully assess their options in light of Argosy&rsquo;s abrupt closure.Â  If students plan to continue their studies in  their current program, the Minnesota Office of Higher Education (&ldquo;OHE&rdquo;) is  working on finding transfer options and other support for students affected by  the closure.Â  If you would like  information related to these issues, you should consult OHE&rsquo;s <a href="https://www.ohe.state.mn.us/mPg.cfm?pageID=2340" target="_blank">Information for Argosy University</a> webpage.Â  </p>
    <p>If you have additional questionsâincluding for example,  about obtaining official transcripts, state financial aid, or specific  programmatic concernsâyou should contact OHE, which can be reached as follows:</p>
    <p class="center"><strong>Minnesota Office of  Higher Education</strong><br>
      1450 Energy Park  Drive, Suite 350<br>
      St. Paul, MN  55108-5227<br>
      Phone: Â (651) 642-0567<br>
    Toll-Free:Â  (800) 657-3866</p>
    <h2>Closed School Discharge of Your Federal  Student Loans</h2>
    <p>The U.S.  Department of Education has posted <a href="https://studentaid.gov/sa/about/announcements/dream-center" target="_blank">information</a> regarding options for Argosy students with federal student loans. This page  includes information about the closure and information about &ldquo;closed school  discharge,&rdquo; which is a mechanism for students who were currently attending  Argosy or withdrew 120 days before closure to apply for discharge of all  federal student loans used to attend the school.Â  </p>
    <p>Students should know, however, that they are generally <strong>not</strong> eligible for closed-school discharge if they:</p>
	<ol class="LINumb">
		<li> withdrew more than 120 days before the main campus or branch  of the main campus&rsquo;s closure;</li>
		<li>are  completing their program through a teach-out agreement with the closed school,  or are transferring the credits they earned at the closed school to a  comparable program at another institution; or</li>
		<li>have  completed all the coursework for their program.</li>
	</ol>
      
      <p>If you are considering closed-school discharge, you  should be aware that completing a comparable program of study through another  school could disqualify you from receiving a closed-school discharge.Â  For example, if you decide to complete a  program in your field of study at another school and you transfer credits  earned at Argosy, you will not be eligible for closed-school discharge of your  Argosy federal loans.Â  For some people,  having their loans discharged will be preferable to continuing their programs  of study and being obligated to repay the student loan debt accrued at their  school.Â  You should carefully consider  your options and personal finances before continuing your studies or applying  for a closed-school discharge. </p>
    <p class="center">***</p>
    <p>The Minnesota Attorney General&rsquo;s Office is also monitoring Dream  Center&rsquo;s federal receivership and coordinating with other agencies and state  attorneys general concerning Argosy&rsquo;s conduct and options for former students  and employees of Argosy.Â  </p>
    <p>For more information about borrower rights related to  student loans, including student&rsquo;s right to apply for closed-school discharge,  students can consult this Office&rsquo;s <a href="/Consumer/Handbooks/StudentLoans/Default.asp">Student  Loan Handbook</a>.Â  To contact the  Attorney General&rsquo;s Office to voice complaints or issues concerning Argosy,  students can contact the Office as follows:</p>
    <p class="center"><strong>Office of Minnesota Attorney General Keith  Ellison</strong><br>
      (651) 296-3353 (Twin Cities Calling Area) or (800) 657-3787 (Outside the  Twin Cities)<br>
      (800) 627-3529 (Minnesota Relay)</p>
